$$\begin{array}{c}
\sqrt{\frac{a^{3}+a b c}{(b+c)^{3}}}-\frac{a}{b+c}=\frac{\sqrt{a}}{b+c} \cdot\left(\sqrt{\frac{a^{2}+b c}{b+c}}-\sqrt{a}\right) \\
=\frac{\sqrt{a}(a-b)(a-c)}{(b+c) \sqrt{b+c}\left(\sqrt{a^{2}+b c}+\sqrt{a(b+c)}\right)}
\end{array}$$

The inequality can be rewritten as $\sum_{c y c} S_{a}(a-b)(a-c) \geq 0$ with
$$\begin{array}{l}
S_{a}=\frac{\sqrt{a}}{(b+c) \sqrt{b+c}\left(\sqrt{a^{2}+b c}+\sqrt{a(b+c)}\right)} \\
S_{b}=\frac{\sqrt{b}}{(c+a) \sqrt{c+a}\left(\sqrt{c^{2}+a b}+\sqrt{c(a+b)}\right)} \\
S_{c}=\frac{\sqrt{c}}{(a+b) \sqrt{a+b}\left(\sqrt{c^{2}+a b}+\sqrt{c(a+b)}\right)}
\end{array}$$

Now suppose that $a \geq b \geq c$, then it's easy to get that
$$\begin{array}{c}
(b+c) \sqrt{a^{2}+b c} \leq(a+c) \sqrt{b^{2}+a c} \\
(b+c) \sqrt{a(b+c)} \leq(a+c) \sqrt{b(a+c)}
\end{array}$$

Thus $(b+c)\left(\sqrt{a^{2}+b c}+\sqrt{a(b+c)}\right) \geq(c+a)\left(\sqrt{c^{2}+a b}+\sqrt{c(a+b)}\right)$ and therefore we have $S_{a} \geq S_{b}$. We can conclude that
$$\begin{aligned}
\sum_{c y c} S_{a}(a-b)(a-c) & \geq S_{a}(a-b)(a-c)+S_{b}(b-a)(b-c) \\
& \geq\left(S_{a}-S_{b}\right)(a-b)(b-c) \geq 0
\end{aligned}$$

This is the end of the proof. The equality holds for $a=b=c$.

